##Donald Trump spoke about the outbreak and announced a number of measures

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

By Sinembo, thepaper.cn

In a nationally televised address to the nation from the White House on the evening of March 11, President Donald Trump announced measures including a travel ban for European countries and emergency aid for businesses and individuals.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
It was Donald Trump's first televised address to the nation on the new crown pneumonia outbreak. Earlier in the day, who director-general Tan Desai announced that the new crown epidemic has constituted a global pandemic.

At the time of publication, more than 1,300 cases had been confirmed in 44 states, according to the Johns Hopkins University.

Accusing the Europeans of "planting" the virus in the United States

In his speech that day, Donald Trump acknowledged the "massive and very dangerous health threat" posed by the new crown pneumonia outbreak to the United States and its citizens, but stressed that "the risk to the vast majority of Americans is very, very low. ".

Donald Trump boasted of his administration's response to the epidemic, saying he had used all the resources of the federal government and the private sector to protect the American people, and said the U.S. government's response to the virus, it is "the most active and comprehensive effort in modern history" .

The travel ban on European countries was the most high profile policy announced by Donald Trump in his speech that day. The policy calls for a 30-day travel ban for the United States and European countries other than the United Kingdom from March 13.

In his televised address, Donald Trump called it a "strong but necessary action" to "protect the health and well-being of the American people. ".

Donald Trump blamed European countries for not taking the same tough measures as the US in the early stages of the epidemic, which has now infected far more people in Europe than in the US, where travellers from Europe have "planted" the virus.

Donald Trump said Americans who had been properly screened could be exempted. The United States Department of Homeland Security later explained that the travel ban does not apply to U.S. citizens returning to the United States, their immediate family members or permanent residents.

The ban also applies to large volumes of trade and the transport of goods, Donald Trump said in a speech on the evening of November 11th. "anything coming into the US from Europe is what we are talking about [ in terms of SCOPE ] , " he said.

However, Donald Trump later explained the opposite on twitter, saying the travel ban does not cover cargo. "It is very important for all countries and businesses to know that trade will not be affected by the 30-day travel ban on Europe, " Donald Trump said. "restrictions prohibit people, not goods. "

Donald Trump said the US would be watching closely to see if the restrictions could be lifted sooner. Donald Trump said the United States may adjust travel restrictions for China and South Korea if the outbreaks improve.

"This is not a financial crisis. "

In addition to the travel ban on European countries, Donald Trump announced several economic and relief measures at home in his speech that day.

Donald Trump said he had met with leaders in the US health insurance industry who have agreed to waive the flat fee for all new coronavirus treatments, expand coverage for those treatments and prevent "unexpected medical bills. ".

Donald Trump noted that last week he signed into law a $8.3 billion emergency fund to fight the pandemic. He says the grant has led to a rapid expansion of testing capabilities in U. S. health agencies.

In practice, however, the Donald Trump administration has been criticized by Congressional Democrats for asking Congress for only $2.5 billion, the $8.3 billion that was the result of bipartisan negotiations. According to U. S. media reports, the current domestic testing capacity there are great challenges.

To ensure that Americans unable to work because of the new pneumonia outbreak do not face financial hardship, Donald Trump said an "unprecedented" emergency financial relief action would be taken soon. He said he would ask Congress to expand such relief.

Donald Trump has boasted of his economic success, saying that the U.S. economy has been the strongest in the world over the past three years because of the economic policies he has adopted. He praised US banks and financial institutions as "well capitalised and surprisingly strong" .

Donald Trump spoke on the same day that the Dow Jones Industrial Average plunged nearly 1,500 points, ending the longest running bull market in the U.S. stock market. "This is not a financial crisis, this is a temporary moment, " Donald Trump said in a televised address

Still, Donald Trump decided to take steps to "provide additional support to American workers, families and businesses" . Among other things, the U.S. Small Business Administration (SBA) was asked to provide capital and liquidity support to businesses affected by the new pneumonia outbreak.

Donald Trump said the policy, which takes effect immediately, will provide low interest loans to affected states and territories to help businesses overcome temporary economic difficulties. To that end, he asked Congress for $50 billion.

Donald Trump also said he would use the emergency authority to instruct the Treasury to defer taxes on certain affected businesses and individuals. This, he claimed, would provide companies with an extra $200bn of liquidity.

Finally, Donald Trump called on Congress to cut payroll taxes immediately, and Donald Trump said, "hopefully they [ Congress ] will take this very seriously. " To offset the negative impact of the new pneumonia epidemic on the U.S. economy, donald Trump on March 10th proposed an economic stimulus plan that would, among other things, reduce payroll taxes that employers and employees pay to pay for government pensions and health care, but was opposed by congressional Democrats.
